    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(center)">Translated from the Curacaische Courant of the <date>24th
                    December 1864</date></p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">The Society “El Porvenir” established in this
                    <placeName>Island</placeName> has<lb/> sumptuously celebrated the first year of
                its existence, on <date>Saturday</date> last<lb/> the <date>17th</date>. Several
                houses and vessels were decorated with flags of different<lb/> nations, which gave a
                beautiful appearance to our harbour. At 7 o'clock<lb/> in the morning and at ½ past
                6 in the afternoon the Dutch Schooner<lb/> “Galgo,” owned by <persName>Mr. Abm. Ib.
                    Jesurun</persName>, left the harbour decorated with flags,<lb/> and fired a
                salute of 21 guns opposite the dwelling of <persName>Mr. Da. Senior Jr.</persName>
                who,<lb/> as Vice-President of above named Society, gave a splendid ball in the
                evening<lb/> of that day in celebration of the festivity. Before the commencement of
                the ball,<lb/> which was numerously attended, <persName>Dr A. M. C.
                    Henriquez</persName> President of the<lb/> Society delivered an address, where
                he developed, in a concise manner &amp; in<lb/> eloquent language, the progress of
                the society during the past year. Afterwards<lb/> a magnificent piece of fire work
                was ignited, which in exploding displayed<lb/> a flag with the following inscription
                “El Provenir, <date>17 Diciembre 1863</date>”</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">The ball lasted <sic>untill</sic> early in the morning of the
                    <date>18th</date> and the guests<lb/> retired most <sic>agreably</sic> impressed
                and highly pleased with the entertainment.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">On the same day the Dutch Reformed Israelitish Congregation
                intro-<lb/>duced for the first time at their divine service singing accompanied by
                an<lb/> Organ. A Cabinet Organ, imported from the <placeName>U. S of
                    America</placeName>, as the most<lb/> appropriate for the building where this
                Cong: keeps its services, has proved<lb/> satisfactory in every respect. The Choir
                was entirely composed of amateurs.<lb/> We cannot refrain from declaring that it has
                in every respect surpassed<lb/> our expectation, and it was clearly to be perceived
                on the countenance of<lb/> those present, what a salutary impression singing &amp;
                music makes on the<lb/> minds of men.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">The solemnity of the service, (which was well attended) was much</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>enhanced by an address given by <persName>Mr A. C. Henriquez</persName>, the object
                of which<lb/> was to point out the utility of music at public worship.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">We wish all happiness &amp; prosperity to the members of the
                new<lb/> congregation.</p>
        </body>
